        <entry>
            <title type="text">The Anatomy of a Predictive Maintenance Project</title>
            <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://localhost:1313/posts/the-anatomy-of-a-predictive-maintenance-project/" />
            <id>http://localhost:1313/posts/the-anatomy-of-a-predictive-maintenance-project/</id>
            <updated>2024-04-25T19:29:53-04:00</updated>
            <published>2024-04-15T00:00:00-04:00</published>
            <author>
                    <name>Ujval Kamath</name>
                    <uri>http://localhost:1313/</uri>
                    </author>
            <rights>[CC BY-NC-SA 4.0](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/deed.en)</rights><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;When conceptualizing and implementing a predictive maintenance project, it can be hard to grasp the entire chain of people and technology needed for success.  In this post I&amp;rsquo;ll try to break down all the people and teams needed for this type of project, and also provide insight into how these people work together.&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
            
            
            
            
            
                
                    
                
                    
                
            
