        <entry>
            <title type="text">Is Your Predictive Maintenance Data Science Program Worth it?</title>
            <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://localhost:1313/posts/is-your-predictive-maintenance-data-science-program-worth-it/" />
            <id>http://localhost:1313/posts/is-your-predictive-maintenance-data-science-program-worth-it/</id>
            <updated>2024-02-26T17:54:55-05:00</updated>
            <published>2024-02-26T00:00:00-04:00</published>
            <author>
                    <name>Ujval Kamath</name>
                    <uri>http://localhost:1313/</uri>
                    </author>
            <rights>[CC BY-NC-SA 4.0](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/deed.en)</rights><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;One mistaken assumption I see people make with predictive maintenance programs is that the cost savings of many lower value projects will add up to a big number, so it&amp;rsquo;s worth putting in the effort.  But sometimes saving a million dollars isn&amp;rsquo;t worth it if it costs you more than that to implement it.  In this post we&amp;rsquo;ll look at four types of programs and understand why some of them aren&amp;rsquo;t worth doing because they have a negative return-on-investment (ROI)&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
            
            
            
            
            
                
                    
                
                    
                
            
        </entry>
    
        <entry>
            <title type="text">Deciding what Data to Collect</title>
            <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://localhost:1313/posts/deciding-what-data-to-collect/" />
            <id>http://localhost:1313/posts/deciding-what-data-to-collect/</id>
            <updated>2024-01-30T10:17:17-05:00</updated>
            <published>2024-01-23T00:00:00-04:00</published>
            <author>
                    <name>Ujval Kamath</name>
                    <uri>http://localhost:1313/</uri>
                    </author>
            <rights>[CC BY-NC-SA 4.0](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/deed.en)</rights><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;In my &lt;a href=&#34;http://localhost:1313/posts/businesses-stakeholders-define-why-data-should-be-collected/&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;previous post&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, we looked at how stakeholders and organizational structures influence decisions about what data is collected and exposed for use.  If you haven&amp;rsquo;t seen machine data before, that post might have felt a little abstract and some things might have felt contradictory (e.g. how does one look at the events before a failure without any sensor data?).  For people who prefer concrete details and real examples, this post is for you.&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
            
            
            
            
            
                
                    
                
                    
                
            
        </entry>
    
        <entry>
            <title type="text">Businesses Stakeholders are the ones who Define why Data Should be Collected</title>
            <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="http://localhost:1313/posts/businesses-stakeholders-define-why-data-should-be-collected/" />
            <id>http://localhost:1313/posts/businesses-stakeholders-define-why-data-should-be-collected/</id>
            <updated>2024-01-19T00:00:00-04:00</updated>
            <published>2024-01-01T00:00:00-04:00</published>
            <author>
                    <name>Ujval Kamath</name>
                    <uri>http://localhost:1313/</uri>
                    </author>
            <rights>[CC BY-NC-SA 4.0](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/deed.en)</rights><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;This post will be the first of two that discusses how organizational dynamics, stakeholder incentives, and the goals of the business drive decisions about what data is collected and why.  What is discussed is relevant to companies trying to do predictive maintenance on industrial and commercial machines, but it applies to other industries as well.&lt;/p&gt;</summary>
            
            
            
            
            
                
                    
                
                    
                
            
